N. tabacum
.

Standard mono- and bi-dimensional NMR experiments have been used for the identification and structural elucidation of SEs and NSEs. Also, the NMR analyses may provide a detailed overview of the organic acid substituted on the sucrose moiety, as well as, the regiochemistry (

; 

; 

).

In regarding to the regiochemistry characterization of the SEs and NSEs, the acylated hydroxyl group on the sucrose moiety can be determined by changes in the chemical shift (δ) of the hydrogen and carbon atoms of the sucrose esters compared to sucrose. These changes in the δ may be observed by mono-dimensional NMR. For example, a shift of +0.5 ppm can be observed for the hydrogen atom which is in the α- position next to the acylated hydroxyl group. In addition, the directly acylated carbon and those next to it can undergo changes of 
ca.
+1–2 ppm and 
ca.
−2 ppm, respectively (

; 

; 

).

The identification of SEs and NSEs with long-chain fatty acids as substituents such as lauric, capric, myristic, caprylic acid, among others (

